        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In this experiment, we intend to detect CO (1-0) at a redshift of z=0.12 and use the remaining three spectral windows to observe the dust continuum at 100 GHz. All line-free channels in the spectral line windows will be used to increase the continuum sensitivity. 

The largest angular scale in the dust emission expected is of order 10" (the size of the HI detection); thus we do not request time with the ACA for this project.

We base our continuum sensitivity estimates on dust with a temperature of 25K and Beta=2; we can reach a sensitivity of 7uJy with our time on source for the spectral line.

For a molecular gas mass of a 2.4e8 solar masses of H2 -- an order of magnitude less massive than the HI detection -- we require a detection of 31 mJy km/s assuming the galactic CO-to-H2 conversion factor. Expecting that the emission will be concentrated in the densest part of the HI, we assume a velocity width of 60 km/s (75% of the width of the HI detection); an (unresolved) 4sigma detection of the above threshold can be made in a 60 km/s channel with an rms of 0.13 mJy in less than 7.5 hours including calibration and overheads.

The spectral setup reflects our redshifted 12CO (J=1-0) line -- the redshift of the line actually brings it farther from the edge of Band 3, which helps our sensitivity -- and the other three windows are set up to observe continuum emission. Assuming ~7 GHz of line free continuum channels, we can reach a continuum sensitivity of 7 uJy in the four hours of on source time needed to detect CO (1-0). There is likely to be cool dust in these galaxies; if so, we can constrain the dust mass in these regions essentially for free. If the dust is heated to 25 K, and we assume beta=2, as well as that the emission follows the Rayleigh-Jeans approximation, then at the 4sigma level, we are sensitive to a few x 10^5 solar masses of dust over IF10V -- a factor of 10^6 less than the stellar mass of the galaxy. 
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
