    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Mapping the evolution of atomic and molecular gas in galaxies over cosmic time is key to understanding how galaxy morphologies change as a function of redshift in the context of hierarchical galaxy evolution. More specifically, though detection rates of cold atomic and molecular gas in early-type galaxies are well known in the nearby Universe (d&lt;42 Mpc), outside of the local volume these parameters are essentially unknown. Until recently, HI observations have been distance-limited due to sensitivity and RFI concerns, but CHILES (a new HI deep field survey at the VLA), will soon enable us to detect neutral hydrogen in galaxies out to z=0.45. We propose to use ALMA to investigate the molecular gas content of IF10V, the single early-type galaxy detected in the pilot CHILES survey, at a redshift of 0.12.</prp:abstract>
